data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration needed.** Your code uses only `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of these are affected by the .NET 6+ `Thread.Abort` breaking change. There are no references to `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or `Thread.Interrupt`. This code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

**Optional modernization:** You could replace the manual thread management with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run` for cleaner code, but this is unrelated to Thread.Abort migration:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This is purely a readability/maintainability improvement — your original code is fully functional on .NET 8.
